collections.name: Safe
collections.description: Safe is a series started just after the 2016 presidential election. One night I went into my daughter’s room and noticed her light was still on. She had probably fallen asleep before she could turn it off. Devastated by the election results, I looked at my child that night, sleeping so soundly and so peacefully, and thought what a breath of fresh air. She was born in a more optimistic time when President Obama was in office and had been for her entire short life. That very night I thought about photographing her but stopped waited to ask her approval. The next day I told her what I was considering and she promptly agreed that I could document her while she slept each night. I was relieved she liked the idea. She had seen and been fascinated by Sally Mann’s “Immediate Family” and Elinor Carrucci’s “Mother” books. She likes the independence of falling asleep at night and now leaves the light on knowing I would be coming up later to take pictures. First using my iPhone and then my Nikon D

collections.name: MACHINE-OBJECTS #1
collections.description:
The concept of machine-objects emerged from my sci-fi short story Machina 20 years ago. It fuses sculpture and equipment, inspired by particle accelerators and cyclotrons—large bolides embedded in urban landscapes. These hybrid, psycho-aesthetic-pedagogical machines blend sculpture and mechanics, incorporating retro-futuristic elements that evoke both past and future.

I question: What is sculpture today? To me, it disrupts the polis, resignifying degraded urban spaces. Machine-objects speak, emit sounds, and project images, reshaping their surroundings. Influences include H.R. Giger (Alien), Alex Raymond (Flash Gordon), and Soviet cubo-futurism (Tatlin, Malevich, Rodchenko, El Lissitzky).

This art engages observers, turning them into participants. It questions existence, thought, and the mechanized lives of modern individuals. It is didactic, provocative, and seeks to educate by breaking routine.

Silvio Barros
Rio de Janeiro, Dec/2024

collections.name: LIST PAINTINGS
collections.description:
Every week, it's the same tedious sermon from the self-anointed Tudor lords of the NFT realm, rolling out their “Top 20” lists like royal decrees. The same faces-always a bit too chummy, a bit too curated-parade through the court, while the rest of us are left tossing cabbages from the mud.

The List Paintings are a glorious, technicolor court jester, prancing through this medieval farce with pop art swagger and punk venom. The blocky, billboard text - VC LISTS, OBEY THE LISTS, TOP 20 NFT LISTS-isn’t just a statement; it’s a chamber pot emptied over the heads of the self-crowned gatekeepers. The AI glitches twist every suit and tie into a carnival of absurdity, exposing the puffed-up pomposity of the mediocrity machine.

This isn’t art that bows or curtsies. It’s a satirical pie to the face, a digital rotten tomato hurled at the powdered wigs of the metaverse elite.

collections.name: Y?
collections.description:
Y? – The Infinite Question
In a world filled with uncertainties, paradoxes, and ever-changing realities, Y? invites you to embrace the unknown. Each NFT in this collection explores the depths of chaos, existence, nature, science, and surreal visions—visual metaphors that challenge perception and provoke thought.

Why do we seek answers? Why do we fear disorder? Why does meaning dissolve in the face of deeper inquiry?

The "Y?" collection is not just art—it is a journey into the fragile balance of reality and imagination. Every piece tells a story, but the ultimate question remains:

Why?
